					<conclusion>
						<p>
							In this section, we explored additional voting systems (the method of pairwise comparisions and instant runoff voting) and fairness criteria (IIA and the monotonicity criterion).
							As we saw that none of our systems satisfied all of our criteria, we were faced with a question: is there <em>any</em> voting system out there that is completely fair?
							Arrow's landmark theorem tells us that no democratic voting system can satisfy all of our criteria.
							This does not mean that our explorations have been fruitless<mdash />instead, we'll need to consider which criteria are most important to us when selecting a voting system, and choose accordingly.
						</p>
